Task 3: Query and Analyze Metrics
Step 3.1: Access Prometheus UI
Open a web browser and navigate to http://<your-machine-ip>:9090

Step 3.2: Execute PromQL Queries
In the Prometheus UI, try these queries:

Query 1: Total HTTP Requests

http_requests_total
Query 2: Request Rate (requests per second)

rate(http_requests_total[1m])
Query 3: Average Request Duration

rate(http_request_duration_seconds_sum[5m]) / rate(http_request_duration_seconds_count[5m])
Query 4: 95th Percentile Request Duration

histogram_quantile(0.95, rate(http_request_duration_seconds_bucket[5m]))
Query 5: Current Health Score

system_health_score
Query 6: Requests by Endpoint

sum by (endpoint) (rate(http_requests_total[1m]))
Step 3.3: Create a Load Generator Script
nano load_generator.sh
Add the following content:

#!/bin/bash

# TODO: Create a script that generates continuous load
# Requirements:
# - Make 100 requests to different endpoints
# - Randomize between /, /api/data, and /health
# - Add random delays between requests (0.1-0.5 seconds)

ENDPOINTS=("/" "/api/data" "/health")

for i in {1..100}; do
    # Select random endpoint
    ENDPOINT=${ENDPOINTS[$RANDOM % ${#ENDPOINTS[@]}]}
    
    # Make request
    curl -s http://localhost:8000$ENDPOINT > /dev/null
    
    # Random delay
    sleep 0.$((RANDOM % 5))
done

echo "Load generation complete"
Make it executable and run:

chmod +x load_generator.sh
./load_generator.sh &
