Troubleshooting
Prometheus Not Starting
# Check logs
sudo journalctl -u prometheus -n 50 --no-pager

# Verify configuration syntax
promtool check config /etc/prometheus/prometheus.yml
Application Metrics Not Appearing
# Verify application is running
ps aux | grep python3

# Check if port 8000 is listening
sudo netstat -tlnp | grep 8000

# Test metrics endpoint directly
curl -v http://localhost:8000/metrics
Metrics Not Updating
# Verify Prometheus is scraping the target
curl http://localhost:9090/api/v1/targets

# Check scrape interval in configuration
cat /etc/prometheus/prometheus.yml | grep scrape_interval
Cleanup
# Stop the application
kill $APP_PID

# Stop load generator if running
pkill -f load_generator.sh

# Stop Prometheus (optional)
sudo systemctl stop prometheus
Conclusion
In this lab, you have:

Installed and configured Prometheus for metrics collection
Instrumented a Python application with four types of Prometheus metrics (Counter, Histogram, Gauge)
Exposed metrics in Prometheus format via an HTTP endpoint
Configured Prometheus to scrape application metrics
Used PromQL to query and analyze system health metrics
Generated load to observe metric behavior in real-time
These skills are essential for DevOps engineers implementing observability in production systems. Prometheus metrics provide the foundation for alerting, capacity planning, and understanding system behavior under various conditions.

Key Takeaways
Metric Types: Counters for cumulative values, Gauges for point-in-time values, Histograms for distributions
Labels: Enable multi-dimensional metrics for detailed analysis
PromQL: Powerful query language for aggregating and analyzing time-series data
Instrumentation: Strategic placement of metrics provides visibility into system health
